WEBVTT

00:14.367 --> 00:17.674
[wind rustling softly]

00:24.464 --> 00:27.162
[flies buzzing]

00:58.976 --> 01:01.805
[shovel banging]

01:07.594 --> 01:10.640
[metallic thudding]

01:11.902 --> 01:14.470
[car beeping]

01:15.558 --> 01:17.734
[engine rumbling]

01:17.821 --> 01:20.389
[tense music]

01:26.917 --> 01:28.919
- You okay?

01:36.275 --> 01:39.103
[high-pitched whining]

01:39.191 --> 01:41.758
[tense music]

01:47.633 --> 01:51.419
[fast-paced heavy breathing]

01:59.124 --> 02:01.517
[screaming]

02:09.090 --> 02:12.093
[luggage rustling]

02:19.318 --> 02:20.449
- Hold on, hold on.

02:20.536 --> 02:21.450
No.

02:22.973 --> 02:25.889
We gotta put the big
black one in first.

02:35.377 --> 02:36.248
No, Meg, hold on.

02:36.334 --> 02:37.596
Just wait, okay?

02:39.338 --> 02:40.208
Okay?

02:41.166 --> 02:42.209
All right, I got it.

02:49.522 --> 02:51.524
[luggage thudding]

02:51.611 --> 02:55.223
[muffled radio chattering]

03:03.188 --> 03:04.406
I grabbed your journal.

03:06.278 --> 03:07.627
It was under the couch.

03:13.720 --> 03:14.764
- You hungry?

03:14.851 --> 03:15.939
- Not really.

03:18.507 --> 03:21.206
[turning signal clicking]

03:21.293 --> 03:22.424
I'm not hungry.

03:24.557 --> 03:26.211
- Okay, but I gotta get gas.

03:28.038 --> 03:28.952
- Fine.

03:30.954 --> 03:31.868
Sorry.

03:45.142 --> 03:48.885
[car doors thudding softly]

03:52.149 --> 03:54.978
[gas pump beeps]

04:01.463 --> 04:03.335
- [Newscaster] City Hall
today, a protest

04:03.422 --> 04:06.903
led by public safety
advocates aims to put pressure

04:06.990 --> 04:08.949
on the Boston police department.

04:09.297 --> 04:10.864
- [Protester] How many
other women and girls

04:10.951 --> 04:13.823
has the Boston police
stopped looking for?

04:13.910 --> 04:17.784
[muffled protesters shouting]

04:19.611 --> 04:21.570
[chip bag crackling]

04:21.657 --> 04:22.528
- [Newscaster] The
department came

04:22.615 --> 04:23.833
under pressure this spring-

04:23.920 --> 04:25.487
- Excuse me.
- After the shocking return

04:25.574 --> 04:26.836
of Megan Rhoads.

04:26.923 --> 04:27.924
The 32-year-old Beacon
Hill resident

04:28.011 --> 04:29.143
[tense music]
[low rumbling]

04:29.230 --> 04:30.927
had been assumed dead
by the police

04:31.014 --> 04:33.452
after she disappeared
from nearby parking garage

04:33.539 --> 04:36.324
nearly six months earlier.

04:41.460 --> 04:44.027
[tense music]

04:48.858 --> 04:50.295
- My great-grandfather
bought this place

04:50.382 --> 04:51.948
in the 20s, I think?

04:55.474 --> 04:58.259
We used to own everything
to the end of that road.

04:58.346 --> 05:00.827
[Meg chuckles softly]

05:26.896 --> 05:29.638
[kisses softly]

05:40.214 --> 05:43.217
[luggage thudding]

05:49.702 --> 05:52.531
[Scott sighs]

05:52.618 --> 05:55.490
[sheets rustling]

06:22.865 --> 06:25.390
[crow cawing]

06:27.522 --> 06:30.395
[Meg gasps]

06:30.525 --> 06:31.831
- Sorry.

06:37.313 --> 06:39.142
- I'll grab the rest
of the bags.

06:39.229 --> 06:40.100
- Okay.

06:49.762 --> 06:52.895
[water whooshing]

06:53.156 --> 06:54.636
Where were your parents?

06:55.507 --> 06:58.031
- The adults all stayed
at the big house, mostly.

06:58.945 --> 06:59.685
Let me get this.

06:59.772 --> 07:01.034
- I got it.

07:01.121 --> 07:02.557
Where's that?

07:02.644 --> 07:04.820
- Well, the big house used
to be down by the beach,

07:04.907 --> 07:07.432
but they tore it down
when I was a kid.

07:07.519 --> 07:08.433
- Why?

07:09.434 --> 07:11.523
- 'Cause no one could
afford the property taxes.

07:11.610 --> 07:12.480
It was massive.

07:15.309 --> 07:16.919
- [Meg] So you were here alone?

07:17.746 --> 07:19.356
- Well, with the rest
of the cousins.

07:19.444 --> 07:21.097
This was like the cousins house.

07:22.229 --> 07:23.839
My grandmother hated
kids, I think,

07:23.926 --> 07:26.102
so she put us all in this house

07:26.189 --> 07:28.888
so she didn't have
to deal with us.

07:28.975 --> 07:29.976
- She sounds sweet.

07:31.586 --> 07:32.805
- No, she wasn't sweet.

07:33.762 --> 07:34.981
We wouldn't see her all summer

07:35.068 --> 07:37.200
and then one day she
would summon us down

07:37.287 --> 07:40.289
and individually interview
us about our interests

07:40.377 --> 07:42.379
and tell us us stand
up straight.

07:44.381 --> 07:45.513
Can I finish this?
- Oh.

07:45.600 --> 07:47.123
[glass clatters loudly]
Shit, sorry.

07:47.210 --> 07:48.124
- I'm sorry.

07:49.082 --> 07:50.562
Meg, you don't have shoes on.

07:50.649 --> 07:52.607
Just back away, it's okay.

07:59.179 --> 08:02.661
[broken glass rustling]

08:02.748 --> 08:05.490
[wine sloshing]

08:10.277 --> 08:13.323
[broken glass clattering]

08:13.410 --> 08:14.934
- Is anyone else coming down?

08:16.283 --> 08:17.197
- Doubt it.

08:18.981 --> 08:20.635
It's pretty empty in the winter.

08:26.075 --> 08:27.337
You sure you didn't...

08:27.424 --> 08:29.252
You alright?
- Yeah, I'm okay.

08:29.339 --> 08:30.689
Thank you.

08:30.776 --> 08:32.559
[Scott chuckles softly]

08:32.821 --> 08:33.953
- My reward.

08:34.039 --> 08:38.958
[Meg chuckles softly]
[tense music]

08:58.064 --> 09:00.719
[Scott sighs]

09:00.806 --> 09:01.676
Good?

09:04.070 --> 09:04.984
You sure?

09:09.989 --> 09:10.859
Come here.

09:16.735 --> 09:19.955
[Scott snores loudly]

09:26.048 --> 09:29.269
[Scott groans softly]

09:30.879 --> 09:33.578
[Scott snores loudly]

09:33.665 --> 09:36.058
[Meg sighs]

09:37.451 --> 09:40.454
[plastic rustling]

10:05.261 --> 10:07.829
[tense music]

10:37.206 --> 10:39.948
[plate rustles]

10:42.603 --> 10:43.517
[dog barks]

10:43.604 --> 10:46.041
[plate clatters sharply]

10:46.128 --> 10:48.653
[tense music]

10:51.960 --> 10:52.831
- Scott?

11:28.562 --> 11:31.870
[Meg breathes shakily]

11:53.413 --> 11:54.327
Scott.

11:56.851 --> 11:57.722
Scott!

11:59.071 --> 12:00.376
[Scott grunts]

12:00.463 --> 12:01.377
Meg.

12:04.076 --> 12:04.946
It's okay.

12:06.513 --> 12:07.601
You're okay.

12:08.950 --> 12:09.995
You're okay.

12:11.823 --> 12:12.867
You're safe.

12:18.786 --> 12:20.440
- You were sleepwalking.

12:20.527 --> 12:21.354
- Hm?

12:21.441 --> 12:22.355
- Last night.

12:28.404 --> 12:29.754
Is there a dog here?

12:30.798 --> 12:31.712
- A dog?

12:34.497 --> 12:39.241
- I heard a dog bark and then
I dropped that weird plate.

12:41.896 --> 12:43.071
- What plate?

12:43.158 --> 12:45.726
[tense music]

12:52.994 --> 12:55.867
- You remember you dropped
a glass last night?

12:56.258 --> 12:59.348
- No, it was right here.

13:02.525 --> 13:03.918
[Scott sighs]

13:04.005 --> 13:06.268
- You remember what
Dr. Potter said?

13:07.748 --> 13:10.403
Sometimes nightmares can
feel really real.

13:13.493 --> 13:16.888
[glass clatters sharply]

13:16.975 --> 13:17.714
You okay?

13:18.977 --> 13:19.716
[Meg exhales shakily]

13:19.804 --> 13:20.543
- Yeah.

13:20.630 --> 13:21.936
[Scott kisses]

13:22.023 --> 13:22.894
- Okay.

13:29.814 --> 13:32.555
[clock ticking]

13:37.952 --> 13:41.260
[Scott rustling beard]

13:46.308 --> 13:49.094
[pages rustling]

13:57.885 --> 14:00.714
[birds chirping]

14:13.988 --> 14:17.122
[door clicks softly]

14:35.009 --> 14:37.316
[tense music]

14:37.403 --> 14:40.232
[sheet rustling]

14:45.715 --> 14:48.718
[eerie vocalizing]

14:52.766 --> 14:55.029
[motorcycle creaking]

14:55.116 --> 14:58.163
[metallic clicking]

15:08.782 --> 15:10.610
[Meg sighs]

15:11.654 --> 15:13.004
[bird chirping]

15:13.526 --> 15:15.789
- I've been thinking
about Christmas.

15:16.659 --> 15:17.573
- Mm-hmm.

15:19.619 --> 15:21.577
- It might be nice to
spend it at home.

15:24.102 --> 15:25.973
- I thought you wanted
to come out here.

15:27.148 --> 15:28.236
- I did, but...

15:28.323 --> 15:30.021
[dog barking]

15:30.108 --> 15:31.283
- [Woman] Yoo-hoo!

15:31.370 --> 15:32.458
- Madelin?

15:32.545 --> 15:35.113
[tense music]

15:38.203 --> 15:40.683
[dog barking]

15:40.770 --> 15:42.250
- Hey, Minnow.

15:42.337 --> 15:43.338
Minnow!

15:43.425 --> 15:44.949
[Minnow barking]
Down!

15:45.036 --> 15:46.385
Down, Minnow!
- Minnow, off.

15:50.215 --> 15:51.738
Talkie. [laughs]
- Madelin.

15:51.825 --> 15:53.131
What are you doing here?

15:53.218 --> 15:56.047
I was just out for a
walk and I saw your car.

15:56.134 --> 15:57.526
I'm staying at my mother's
little shack.

15:57.613 --> 15:58.701
- [Scott] How's your mom doing?

15:58.788 --> 16:00.355
- [Madelin] Not well,
I'm afraid.

16:00.442 --> 16:01.226
- I'm so sorry, that's tough.

16:01.313 --> 16:02.227
- Yeah.

16:03.793 --> 16:08.233
And Meg, I'm so glad
to see you again!

16:08.320 --> 16:09.974
- I'm sorry?

16:10.061 --> 16:13.455
- Meg, this is my
cousin Madelin.

16:13.542 --> 16:14.979
You met her at the wedding.

16:15.066 --> 16:16.415
- Oh.

16:16.502 --> 16:17.633
- We've got a big family.

16:17.720 --> 16:20.767
I won't hold it against
you. [chuckles]

16:21.637 --> 16:24.814
So, how long are you here for?

16:24.901 --> 16:26.599
Not sure.
- Through the New Year.

16:27.556 --> 16:29.776
- I can't believe Talkie
didn't tell me

16:29.863 --> 16:31.343
you two were coming. [laughs]

16:31.430 --> 16:34.389
I didn't know anybody
was gonna be here.

16:34.476 --> 16:35.912
- Talkie?

16:36.000 --> 16:40.395
- Oh, well, Scott was
so quiet as a kid.

16:40.482 --> 16:42.267
I don't think he said
a word until you

16:42.354 --> 16:43.659
were what, two years old?

16:43.746 --> 16:45.009
- Okay, I don't think we
need to talk about this.

16:45.096 --> 16:47.054
- So we started calling
him, you know,

16:47.141 --> 16:48.751
I think it was grandmother
who first...

16:48.838 --> 16:51.450
In any case, we started calling
him walkie-talkie as a joke,

16:51.537 --> 16:55.541
and then just walkie Scotty,
and then just talkie.

16:56.411 --> 16:57.891
- Poor Scott.

16:57.978 --> 16:58.892
- Sorry?

16:59.936 --> 17:03.201
He just told me how tough
your grandmother could be.

17:03.288 --> 17:04.201
- Oh, I was just telling
her about

17:04.289 --> 17:06.291
the famous sit-down interviews.

17:06.507 --> 17:07.466
- Right.

17:10.729 --> 17:13.907
You know, I had a friend
in college named Meg.

17:13.994 --> 17:16.257
It was short for Megumi.

17:16.344 --> 17:17.650
- Oh.

17:17.737 --> 17:19.434
- Is your name short
for anything?

17:21.610 --> 17:22.524
- Megan.

17:24.135 --> 17:25.919
- So you need some
cream and sugar?

17:26.920 --> 17:29.488
- Did you forget how
I take my tea?

17:29.575 --> 17:30.837
- Do you wanna do it yourself-
- Has it been that long?

17:30.924 --> 17:32.186
- -you can just take care of it.

17:32.273 --> 17:34.406
- [Madelin] Has it been
that long? [laughs]

17:34.493 --> 17:37.104
[tense music]

17:49.899 --> 17:54.948
[thudding]
[woman whimpering]

18:00.954 --> 18:04.479
[doors rustling]

18:04.566 --> 18:07.613
[woman whimpering]
[Meg gasps]

18:07.700 --> 18:11.007
[Meg breathes shakily]

18:11.878 --> 18:15.142
[tennis ball thumping]

18:19.755 --> 18:21.453
[Meg exhales shakily]

18:21.540 --> 18:23.324
- Let me see how you're
holding it.

18:23.411 --> 18:24.412
You gotta hold it
like that that.

18:24.499 --> 18:25.544
All right, right here, ready?

18:25.631 --> 18:27.415
- Okay.

18:27.502 --> 18:30.810
[tennis ball thumping]

18:39.427 --> 18:40.167
[Scott grunts]

18:40.254 --> 18:40.994
- Yes!

18:41.081 --> 18:42.256
Nice shot, Madelin.

18:42.343 --> 18:44.476
[Madelin laughing]

18:44.563 --> 18:45.912
- I've got it.

18:45.999 --> 18:49.655
[Meg grunts loudly]

18:49.742 --> 18:50.873
- [Scott] I'll get it.

18:53.093 --> 18:54.529
- It's okay.

18:54.616 --> 18:56.792
- Oh, it is really
back here, Meg.

18:56.879 --> 18:57.967
- Sorry.

18:59.404 --> 19:00.535
- It's lodged deep.

19:00.622 --> 19:02.581
[tense music]
You know, it helps

19:02.668 --> 19:07.629
if you square your hips
and start low.

19:08.543 --> 19:10.502
Keep your eye on the ball.

19:10.589 --> 19:13.331
Swing through all the way over.

19:15.985 --> 19:16.725
- Yeah?

19:16.812 --> 19:18.292
- [Scott] Got it.

19:19.598 --> 19:20.773
- Why don't we just rally?

19:20.860 --> 19:23.906
Give Meg a chance to
get her bearings.

19:32.088 --> 19:34.874
[paper rustling]

19:42.403 --> 19:47.452
[Meg breathes heavily]
[clothes rustling]

19:57.462 --> 19:59.333
[door creaks]

19:59.420 --> 20:01.988
[tense music]

20:07.080 --> 20:10.214
[footsteps thudding]

20:21.442 --> 20:22.704
[Meg whimpering]

20:22.791 --> 20:23.879
- Meg, Meg, Meg, Meg,
Meg, Meg, Meg, Meg.

20:23.966 --> 20:27.056
[Meg crying loudly]

20:28.144 --> 20:28.884
[high-pitched whining]

20:28.971 --> 20:30.625
It's not, it's not.

20:45.118 --> 20:48.034
[calm vocalizing]

21:08.881 --> 21:10.926
- I used to count the footsteps.

21:11.013 --> 21:13.755
[clock ticking]

21:15.540 --> 21:17.106
The house was old.

21:22.634 --> 21:23.983
The sound carried.

21:37.605 --> 21:38.998
I started counting

21:42.741 --> 21:44.308
how long it would
take them to get

21:44.395 --> 21:46.266
to different places
in the house.

21:56.624 --> 22:01.673
It helped a little

22:02.978 --> 22:05.807
to always know how long it
would take them to get to me.

22:10.986 --> 22:14.076
[Scott sighs]

22:14.163 --> 22:16.601
[Meg sighs]

22:17.558 --> 22:19.952
- Dr. Potter said it
could be really helpful

22:21.040 --> 22:22.346
to write in your journal

22:26.741 --> 22:28.656
when you're having
moments like this.

22:43.671 --> 22:44.933
Can I go get it for you?

22:49.764 --> 22:52.550
[glass clinking]

22:53.855 --> 22:57.076
So this is an Argentinian wine.

22:57.163 --> 23:00.645
It's supposed to be really
good, sort of peppery.

23:05.737 --> 23:06.651
Good?

23:07.913 --> 23:09.436
- Good.

23:09.523 --> 23:12.047
I dunno.

23:12.134 --> 23:13.875
- No, [laughs] wait,
what are you doing?

23:13.962 --> 23:15.834
- You hate it.
- No, I love it.

23:15.921 --> 23:17.444
- And you're sure?
- Yes.

23:17.531 --> 23:18.706
- And you wanna drink it?
- Mm-hmm, I wanna drink it.

23:18.793 --> 23:20.273
- We have others.
- No, I want this one.

23:20.360 --> 23:21.187
[Meg laughs softly]

23:21.274 --> 23:22.536
Put the wine down, psycho.

23:22.623 --> 23:25.974
[Minnow barking]
- Yoo-hoo!

23:26.061 --> 23:27.846
Minnow, down.

23:27.933 --> 23:30.718
Off.
[Minnow panting]

23:30.805 --> 23:32.024
Oh.

23:32.111 --> 23:32.894
Hello.

23:32.981 --> 23:33.852
- Hello, hello, hello.

23:33.939 --> 23:35.114
[Madelin kisses animatedly]

23:35.201 --> 23:37.682
I brought chicken
and an eggplant.

23:37.769 --> 23:39.640
- Oh, you didn't have to.

23:39.727 --> 23:40.989
- Oh, my mother barely
eats anyway

23:41.076 --> 23:42.382
and I don't want all
this to go to waste.

23:42.469 --> 23:44.253
Here, would you get
to work on this?

23:44.340 --> 23:49.171
- Oh, actually, I'm sorry,
we weren't expecting you.

23:50.521 --> 23:52.479
- Oh, god, so American.

23:52.566 --> 23:54.438
What is it, five o'clock?
[laughs]

23:54.525 --> 23:56.048
- [Scott] 6:30.

23:56.135 --> 23:58.267
- If you got to a restaurant
in Paris at eight o'clock,

23:58.354 --> 23:59.921
you'd be the first ones there.

24:00.922 --> 24:01.662
- You know what?

24:01.749 --> 24:02.489
We can have it tomorrow.

24:02.576 --> 24:03.447
- Yeah.

24:03.534 --> 24:04.448
Thank you.

24:08.539 --> 24:11.193
[Scott sighs]

24:11.280 --> 24:12.934
- Well, I better be off.

24:16.982 --> 24:18.853
- Would you like to
stay for dinner?

24:18.940 --> 24:19.680
- That's a good idea.

24:19.767 --> 24:21.203
- No, I couldn't impose.

24:21.290 --> 24:22.509
- No, it's not an imposition.

24:22.596 --> 24:23.728
I can just set out an extra...

24:23.815 --> 24:24.903
- Alright, well, wonderful.

24:24.990 --> 24:25.817
Talkie, get out the
good glasses.

24:25.904 --> 24:28.472
I have a surprise for you.

24:30.386 --> 24:31.823
- Is that the family rye?

24:31.910 --> 24:33.868
- The last batch. [laughs]

24:33.955 --> 24:35.479
- You make your own whiskey?

24:35.566 --> 24:36.958
- Yeah, well, our
great-grandfather-

24:37.045 --> 24:38.307
- Great-great-grandfather.

24:38.394 --> 24:40.092
- Our great-great-grandfather
was a banker

24:40.179 --> 24:44.313
and a man owed him money, and
after the markets crashed,

24:44.400 --> 24:45.489
he couldn't pay in cash so-

24:45.576 --> 24:50.232
- So Pop let him pay
us in whiskey.

24:50.319 --> 24:53.845
- We've had a basement full
of stuff for almost a century,

24:53.932 --> 24:55.237
but we're almost out now.

24:56.325 --> 24:58.893
- To the fall of
our great house.

25:00.068 --> 25:03.028
[glasses clinking]

25:08.729 --> 25:10.252
[Meg coughs]

25:10.339 --> 25:13.168
- Let me just grab the wine
and then we will be ready.

25:13.255 --> 25:15.083
[Madelin chuckles]

25:15.170 --> 25:16.998
- Looks delicious, Talkie.

25:17.085 --> 25:17.999
- Yeah.

25:22.177 --> 25:25.398
[silverware scraping]

25:30.751 --> 25:32.927
- How are things at the firm?

25:33.014 --> 25:36.409
- Oh, yeah, I'm still on
leave through the holidays,

25:36.496 --> 25:40.413
but yeah, I spoke to the
partners and they
were suggesting

25:40.500 --> 25:42.284
a January 10th return.

25:42.371 --> 25:43.068
- [Madelin] Oh, that's
wonderful.

25:43.155 --> 25:44.069
- What?

25:44.939 --> 25:45.897
- I told you that.

25:47.376 --> 25:52.425
- And Meg, Scotty tells
me you were an engineer.

25:53.905 --> 25:54.906
- Am.

25:54.993 --> 25:55.994
- Hm?

25:56.081 --> 25:57.735
- I am an engineer.

25:57.822 --> 25:59.650
I'm also returning to
work in the new year.

25:59.737 --> 26:02.261
- Oh, that's fantastic news.

26:02.348 --> 26:03.915
Scotty didn't mention it.

26:04.002 --> 26:05.786
- Yeah, thank you.

26:05.873 --> 26:06.744
- When?

26:08.833 --> 26:10.530
When are you going back?

26:12.227 --> 26:14.403
- I'm not exactly sure yet.

26:14.490 --> 26:16.884
They're still reconfiguring
my position.

26:16.971 --> 26:18.364
- Of course.

26:18.451 --> 26:19.670
I'm sure they had to
shuffle things around a bit

26:19.757 --> 26:20.671
when you got back.

26:25.937 --> 26:27.460
- What do you do?

26:27.547 --> 26:29.767
- Oh, a little of this,
a little of that.

26:29.854 --> 26:33.031
I take care of my mother,
and then there's the land.

26:33.118 --> 26:35.076
That just never stops.

26:35.163 --> 26:37.905
- Madelin actually taught
in Korea after college.

26:37.992 --> 26:39.559
Meg was born in Seoul.

26:40.342 --> 26:41.300
- Oh!

26:41.387 --> 26:45.130
[speaking Korean]

26:47.828 --> 26:50.701
- Sorry, I don't speak Korean.

26:50.788 --> 26:53.355
- Oh, [laughs] don't
worry about it.

26:53.442 --> 26:54.966
I just asked when you left.

26:56.184 --> 27:00.711
- Oh, I was adopted
when I was three.

27:02.669 --> 27:04.976
- Oh.
- Can you pass the salt?

27:05.063 --> 27:05.977
- Yeah.

27:08.849 --> 27:10.851
- So I ran into the
Harrisons at the market.

27:10.938 --> 27:12.113
- I heard they were selling.

27:12.200 --> 27:12.984
- [Scott] Indeed, they are.

27:13.071 --> 27:15.290
[Madelin gasps]

27:15.377 --> 27:16.161
Their neighbors
[Minnow whimpering]

27:16.248 --> 27:16.988
bought the property.

27:17.075 --> 27:18.511
- Uh-huh.

27:18.598 --> 27:19.643
- They're putting in a
pool over the entire lot.

27:19.730 --> 27:20.861
- [Madelin] Oh.

27:20.948 --> 27:21.993
- [Scott] Tearing down
the old house.

27:22.080 --> 27:22.994
- Stop it.

27:26.214 --> 27:29.740
You teach a dog to beg,
it'll never stop.

27:35.310 --> 27:36.311
- Pass the salad.

27:39.663 --> 27:44.668
[water whooshing]
[plates clinking]

27:54.852 --> 27:57.245
- How are you guys
related again?

27:57.332 --> 27:58.464
- [Scott] We're cousins.

28:00.553 --> 28:01.685
- Like first cousins?

28:03.208 --> 28:04.818
- Our dads are brothers, why?

28:07.038 --> 28:07.908
- Nothing.

28:14.088 --> 28:14.959
It's just

28:18.702 --> 28:21.182
what was with Madelin
speaking in Korean to me?

28:23.707 --> 28:25.796
- I think she was just
trying to connect.

28:27.754 --> 28:31.149
- Okay, but I also have
family in Sweden.

28:32.324 --> 28:35.022
I bet she wouldn't have tried
to speak in Swedish to me.

28:36.197 --> 28:39.244
- Well, I don't think she
speaks Swedish, but okay.

28:40.419 --> 28:42.769
[Meg sighs]

28:42.856 --> 28:44.379
[Scott sighs]

28:44.466 --> 28:46.512
Do you want me to talk
to her about it?

28:46.599 --> 28:48.557
- No, thank you.

28:53.214 --> 28:55.608
[Meg sighs]

28:56.783 --> 28:57.697
- I know.

29:02.354 --> 29:04.486
It's always made me kind
of uncomfortable,

29:06.662 --> 29:10.579
but I [laughs] can't control
what they put on their walls.

29:10.666 --> 29:11.755
- [Meg] Yeah.

29:11.842 --> 29:13.452
- [Scott] And it was
a long time ago.

29:16.890 --> 29:17.761
- But...

29:18.718 --> 29:19.458
[Scott sighs]

29:19.545 --> 29:20.720
- What?

29:20.807 --> 29:23.462
- Well, what did your
grandparents do

29:23.549 --> 29:24.855
when they were over there?

29:24.942 --> 29:27.379
- My great grandparents
were missionaries.

29:27.466 --> 29:30.425
- So they built churches and
taught people English, right?

29:31.209 --> 29:32.863
- Right.

29:32.950 --> 29:37.650
- Okay, and what did Madelin
do when she was over there?

29:37.737 --> 29:39.826
- Okay, she taught
at a university.

29:39.913 --> 29:41.175
- She taught English! [laughs]

29:41.262 --> 29:42.350
- It's not the same thing.

29:42.437 --> 29:43.743
- Really?

29:43.830 --> 29:45.310
'Cause it feels like a
different iteration

29:45.397 --> 29:46.659
of the same thing to me.

29:47.921 --> 29:50.489
[Scott sighs]

29:56.582 --> 29:59.367
- Well, I guess we
just disagree.

30:02.283 --> 30:03.850
We can disagree, right?

30:08.246 --> 30:09.160
- Yeah.

30:12.990 --> 30:13.860
- Okay.

30:15.906 --> 30:18.430
[Meg gasps]

30:18.517 --> 30:21.825
[Meg breathes shakily]

30:27.526 --> 30:30.094
[tense music]

30:36.491 --> 30:37.405
- Scott?

30:43.281 --> 30:44.804
[high-pitched whining]

30:44.891 --> 30:47.633
[slow thudding]

31:17.010 --> 31:19.534
[Man whistles]

31:19.621 --> 31:22.624
[muffled shouting]

31:25.889 --> 31:26.802
- Hi.

31:34.506 --> 31:36.247
- You gotta stay below
the water line

31:36.334 --> 31:38.031
if you're gonna walk
around here.

31:40.686 --> 31:41.600
- Why?

31:42.514 --> 31:43.819
- It's private property.

31:45.125 --> 31:46.735
- Are you a Whitman?

31:46.822 --> 31:47.911
[Man laughs]

31:47.998 --> 31:49.173
- No, I just do some
repairs for them

31:49.260 --> 31:50.870
in exchange for fishing rights.

31:52.002 --> 31:54.047
They're really uptight
about trespassing.

31:58.051 --> 32:02.186
- I'm actually here with
my husband, Scott Whitman.

32:04.492 --> 32:05.841
- Shit, sorry, I'm an idiot.

32:05.929 --> 32:06.842
- [Meg] [laughs] No, it's fine.

32:06.930 --> 32:08.409
- I didn't realize he was back.

32:08.496 --> 32:10.629
Yeah, the summer crowd
doesn't usually come so often

32:10.716 --> 32:11.891
during the off season.

32:16.287 --> 32:17.766
- What do you mean so often?

32:19.551 --> 32:22.902
- Nothing, just he was here
last winter for a while.

32:25.949 --> 32:32.042
Hey, I'm really sorry
about what happened to you.

32:36.089 --> 32:37.134
- Thank you.

32:46.665 --> 32:49.233
[tense music]

32:53.324 --> 32:56.370
[door thuds softly]

33:05.075 --> 33:08.295
Why have we never come out here?

33:08.382 --> 33:10.254
- There's just so much baggage,

33:11.081 --> 33:13.431
so much family stuff out here.

33:13.518 --> 33:15.737
I guess I'm realizing that

33:17.522 --> 33:19.741
it's been so long since
I've been out here.

33:22.179 --> 33:24.224
I'm glad we're here now.

33:30.317 --> 33:33.016
[coat rustling]

33:34.669 --> 33:37.977
[garage door rumbling]

33:39.892 --> 33:42.329
[wrench clicking]

33:42.416 --> 33:44.723
[screwdriver clicking]

33:44.810 --> 33:47.639
[parts rustling]

33:55.516 --> 33:58.128
[pencil scratching]

33:58.215 --> 34:00.782
[tense music]

34:01.870 --> 34:05.352
[both breathing heavily]

34:13.317 --> 34:15.275
[door thuds]

34:15.362 --> 34:16.755
- Stay with me.

34:19.932 --> 34:21.019
[door thuds loudly]

34:21.106 --> 34:23.675
[tense music]

34:25.981 --> 34:26.939
[door banging loudly]

34:27.026 --> 34:30.334
[high-pitched whining]

34:50.396 --> 34:52.747
[high-pitched whining]

34:52.834 --> 34:53.617
See?

34:53.704 --> 34:55.228
Everything's fine.

35:04.498 --> 35:08.111
[glass clattering sharply]

35:25.519 --> 35:28.087
[tense music]

36:01.468 --> 36:04.950
[Madelin singing eerily]

36:23.621 --> 36:25.275
- Shit.
- Meg!

36:26.189 --> 36:29.670
[Madelin laughing]

36:29.757 --> 36:32.151
Go in, go in, I'll
be right there!

36:37.722 --> 36:39.506
[footsteps thumping]

36:39.593 --> 36:42.074
It's incredible for
the immune system,

36:42.161 --> 36:44.468
the cold air and hot
water together.

36:44.555 --> 36:46.426
I haven't been sick in years.

36:46.513 --> 36:48.602
- Oh, thank you.

36:48.689 --> 36:49.603
- Mm-hmm.

36:53.390 --> 36:55.740
My mother became obsessed
with oil painting

36:55.827 --> 36:56.958
when she got sick.

36:58.133 --> 36:59.918
Can't tell you how many
hours we sat like that,

37:00.005 --> 37:01.049
posing for her.

37:02.703 --> 37:03.922
- You used to be blonde?

37:05.489 --> 37:06.359
- Briefly.

37:08.840 --> 37:10.233
- It doesn't look like you.

37:11.886 --> 37:13.540
- She wasn't a great painter.

37:14.411 --> 37:17.457
[Meg laughs softly]

37:18.763 --> 37:19.981
- Who's the little boy?

37:21.722 --> 37:22.636
- My brother.

37:25.204 --> 37:26.074
- Your brother?

37:28.990 --> 37:32.255
- He died when he was
five and I was eight.

37:34.126 --> 37:36.041
We were swimming right
off our beach.

37:40.611 --> 37:41.481
- I'm sorry.

37:42.656 --> 37:44.267
- For most of my childhood,
I thought I dreamt

37:44.354 --> 37:45.398
the whole thing.

37:45.485 --> 37:47.052
My parents never talked
about him.

37:47.922 --> 37:49.837
I don't know what possessed
my mother to paint him

37:49.924 --> 37:50.969
into that portrait.

37:52.710 --> 37:54.712
I'm not even sure it's
a good likeness.

38:04.112 --> 38:06.027
- I think I saw her earlier.

38:08.160 --> 38:09.074
- Who?

38:10.597 --> 38:13.557
- Your mother, walking
in the woods.

38:15.428 --> 38:16.777
- My mother is bedridden.

38:18.301 --> 38:20.128
She hasn't left that
room in months.

38:21.521 --> 38:22.392
- Oh.

38:32.489 --> 38:34.012
How is she?

38:34.099 --> 38:35.013
- She's dying.

38:36.710 --> 38:37.581
- I'm sorry.

38:38.756 --> 38:41.062
- She hasn't enjoyed
life for many years.

38:42.455 --> 38:44.457
Death will be a mercy.

38:44.544 --> 38:47.112
[tense music]

38:49.549 --> 38:50.550
Coyotes.

38:52.117 --> 38:53.684
They can be a real menace.

38:59.342 --> 39:01.126
Mm, what's that?

39:03.824 --> 39:05.348
- Oh, it's nothing.

39:05.435 --> 39:06.827
Just a nervous habit.

39:06.914 --> 39:08.394
- What are you nervous about?

39:09.874 --> 39:11.136
- Nothing.

39:11.223 --> 39:12.790
- Is it all the talk of death?

39:14.269 --> 39:15.706
[Madelin chuckles]

39:15.793 --> 39:17.055
Are you afraid of dying?

39:18.970 --> 39:19.971
- Everyone is.

39:20.058 --> 39:21.059
- Not everyone.

39:22.582 --> 39:24.845
Some people believe we
go somewhere better.

39:26.760 --> 39:31.112
Other people think anywhere
is better than here.

39:39.556 --> 39:40.905
- May I use your bathroom?

39:42.515 --> 39:44.212
- Right at the top
of the stairs.

39:53.874 --> 39:56.703
[low rumbling]

39:56.790 --> 39:57.661
- Wrong way.

39:58.879 --> 40:00.751
[Meg chuckles awkwardly]

40:00.838 --> 40:01.665
Upstairs.

40:04.145 --> 40:07.322
[footsteps thumping]

40:10.674 --> 40:13.546
[low rumbling]

40:13.633 --> 40:14.765
[door clicks]

40:14.852 --> 40:17.985
[footsteps clicking]

40:19.683 --> 40:22.033
[door thuds]

40:22.120 --> 40:24.470
[garbage clattering]

40:24.557 --> 40:25.906
- Fuck!

40:25.993 --> 40:28.474
[Meg grunts]

40:35.916 --> 40:38.441
[tense music]

40:42.270 --> 40:45.883
- Yoo-hoo!
[Minnow barking]

40:50.975 --> 40:52.193
So I steal the keys.

40:52.280 --> 40:53.673
- Naturally, I stole
the booze. [laughs]

40:53.760 --> 40:56.502
- And we get out on the
water and it's pitch black

40:56.589 --> 40:58.461
on the water, and I
look at Madelin,

40:58.548 --> 41:01.072
I hand her the keys, and that's
when we realized [laughs]

41:01.159 --> 41:03.814
neither of us knows how
to drive a boat.

41:03.901 --> 41:07.034
So we just floated for a
little while and about an hour

41:07.121 --> 41:10.516
into it, we realize we have
drifted well off our mooring,

41:10.603 --> 41:13.084
like out into the bay,
and suddenly Madelin

41:13.171 --> 41:14.520
gets a look of confidence.

41:14.607 --> 41:15.869
- I mean, gin can do
that to a girl, you know?

41:15.956 --> 41:17.784
- And she declares, "I'm
gonna drive us back."

41:17.871 --> 41:19.307
- [Madelin] Yeah, and I did!

41:19.394 --> 41:20.961
- Well, you did,
but you drove us

41:21.048 --> 41:23.660
right into the neighbor's dock,
to be fair. [Madelin laughs]

41:23.747 --> 41:25.183
So if the boat is totaled.

41:25.270 --> 41:27.620
Their dock is like splinters.

41:27.707 --> 41:28.578
She looks at me.

41:28.665 --> 41:29.317
You remember what you said?

41:29.404 --> 41:30.623
I'll never forget.

41:30.710 --> 41:32.146
[Madelin clears throat]

41:32.233 --> 41:33.974
- "Do you think mother will
notice the gin is gone?"

41:34.061 --> 41:36.803
[both laughing]

41:41.155 --> 41:42.243
- I love that story.

41:42.330 --> 41:43.506
Oh, man.

41:43.593 --> 41:44.768
- So what did you do?

41:46.639 --> 41:47.901
- About what?

41:49.816 --> 41:51.035
- The boat.

41:51.122 --> 41:52.689
The dock.

41:52.776 --> 41:56.127
- [Madelin] Oh, we had it
repaired, I mean. [laughs]

41:56.214 --> 41:57.520
- Must have been expensive.

41:57.607 --> 41:58.521
- Mm-mm.

41:59.347 --> 42:01.524
We don't talk about money
at the dinner table.

42:08.661 --> 42:10.054
- But we're already talking
about money.

42:10.141 --> 42:12.186
- Meg, it's just a story.

42:13.579 --> 42:14.624
- What do you mean?

42:15.450 --> 42:17.540
- Well, that's what this
whole story is about.

42:18.802 --> 42:19.890
[Scott sighs]

42:19.977 --> 42:21.065
It's fine.

42:22.327 --> 42:23.676
I'm not saying it's bad.

42:24.547 --> 42:25.722
I just think it's funny.

42:26.636 --> 42:29.334
Only rich people think it's
rude to talk about money.

42:33.033 --> 42:36.254
- It's interesting you don't
consider yourself rich.

42:37.734 --> 42:38.952
- Well, it's different.

42:40.301 --> 42:42.260
I didn't grow up with money.

42:42.347 --> 42:44.915
- But you have money now.

42:45.002 --> 42:48.092
- My parents' life
insurance, not a trust fund.
- Because as I understand
it, you actually have

42:48.179 --> 42:50.573
a good deal more money
than either Scott or me.

42:53.619 --> 42:55.403
I'm not saying it's bad.

42:55.490 --> 42:58.711
[wine sloshing]

42:58.798 --> 42:59.669
Just funny.

43:02.933 --> 43:06.240
[Meg chuckles quietly]

43:14.771 --> 43:16.033
This has been lovely.

43:17.164 --> 43:19.602
I should really go check
on my mother.

43:19.689 --> 43:20.690
- Oh.

43:20.777 --> 43:22.082
- Oh, I'm sorry.

43:22.169 --> 43:23.127
- Yeah, I'll just...

43:23.214 --> 43:24.781
If you're not done, we can...

43:30.961 --> 43:33.006
[Meg laughs quietly]

43:33.093 --> 43:34.007
- I'm done.

43:34.094 --> 43:35.008
It's fine.

43:36.270 --> 43:37.402
- She'll eat it later.

43:40.318 --> 43:41.232
- It's fine.

43:45.715 --> 43:47.978
- She doesn't like to eat
in front of people anymore.

43:56.247 --> 43:57.640
- [Madelin] You poor thing.

44:06.039 --> 44:08.607
[chair bangs]

44:11.436 --> 44:14.613
[Meg chewing loudly]

44:31.674 --> 44:34.154
[fork clangs]

44:34.241 --> 44:35.155
- All done.

44:41.901 --> 44:44.382
[door bangs]

44:51.432 --> 44:53.783
[door creaking]

44:53.870 --> 44:56.916
[drawer rustling]

44:57.003 --> 44:59.876
[sheets rustling]

45:08.101 --> 45:11.322
So we're just not gonna
talk about it.

45:15.282 --> 45:17.850
[Scott sighs]

45:33.300 --> 45:34.649
- They poisoned your food.

45:36.042 --> 45:39.089
Not every time, but
enough to keep you scared.

45:42.527 --> 45:44.181
And I'm sorry, I don't...

45:45.791 --> 45:47.575
I'm sorry they did that to you.

45:54.539 --> 45:58.021
[Scott breathes shakily]

46:05.768 --> 46:07.770
- They made me make videos.

46:08.945 --> 46:10.511
[tense music]

46:10.598 --> 46:14.428
They made me beg you for help.

46:16.866 --> 46:17.780
- Not tonight.

46:21.174 --> 46:22.393
- Are you serious?

46:22.480 --> 46:23.437
- [Scott] I'm tired,
I'm not doing this.

46:23.524 --> 46:24.699
- We're having a conversation.

46:24.787 --> 46:25.700
- No, we're not!

46:25.788 --> 46:26.658
- You can't just decide that!

46:26.745 --> 46:29.226
[door slams]

46:38.235 --> 46:41.542
[high-pitched whining]

47:06.829 --> 47:09.440
[Meg breathes shakily]

47:09.527 --> 47:12.791
[garage door creaking]

47:14.880 --> 47:17.709
[parts rustling]

47:19.580 --> 47:21.365
[screwdriver scraping]

47:21.452 --> 47:23.236
[wrench clicking]

47:23.323 --> 47:26.370
[metallic clacking]

47:43.300 --> 47:46.956
[motorcycle creaking]

47:47.043 --> 47:48.131
[metallic clicking]

47:48.218 --> 47:51.134
[high-pitched whining]
[slow music]

47:51.221 --> 47:54.093
[engine rumbling]

48:21.425 --> 48:24.297
[engine rumbling]

48:34.133 --> 48:36.701
[door creaking]

48:36.788 --> 48:41.836
[slow jazzy music]
[muffled singing]

48:45.144 --> 48:48.278
[patrons chattering]

48:52.325 --> 48:55.372
[Meg clears throat]

49:00.899 --> 49:03.293
[Man sighs]

49:10.300 --> 49:11.214
- Look who it is.

49:14.913 --> 49:16.436
- Oh, hey.

49:20.571 --> 49:23.095
- Never thought I'd run
into a Whitman woman here.

49:24.618 --> 49:26.229
- Thanks.
- I'm not a Whitman.

49:28.100 --> 49:28.971
- You what?

49:31.582 --> 49:33.540
- I kept my last name.

49:34.411 --> 49:35.629
It's Rhoads.

49:39.198 --> 49:40.069
- I'm Joe.

49:42.332 --> 49:43.202
- Meg.

49:44.508 --> 49:45.813
- Not Whitman.

49:45.900 --> 49:47.293
[Meg laughs]

49:47.380 --> 49:48.251
- Not Whitman.

49:51.906 --> 49:53.952
- So how long are
you in town for?

49:55.301 --> 49:56.694
- Too long.

49:56.781 --> 49:58.087
- [Joe] You don't like it here?

49:59.958 --> 50:01.264
- It's a little...

50:01.351 --> 50:02.221
- Lonely.

50:04.267 --> 50:06.399
- [Meg] I was gonna
say claustrophobic.

50:06.486 --> 50:09.402
[Joe laughs]

50:09.489 --> 50:10.360
- [Joe] Thanks.

50:14.364 --> 50:15.800
- Hey, do you know Madelin?

50:16.583 --> 50:18.063
- [Joe] Madelin?

50:18.150 --> 50:19.978
- My husband's cousin?

50:20.065 --> 50:21.284
- Mm.

50:21.371 --> 50:22.763
Oh, yeah.

50:22.850 --> 50:24.852
I mean, I don't know her,
but I see her around.

50:25.766 --> 50:27.029
- And my husband Scott.

50:28.465 --> 50:31.381
You saw him around
too, last winter?

50:32.991 --> 50:34.906
- Yeah, a couple times.

50:36.864 --> 50:38.649
- Were they here at
the same time?

50:40.085 --> 50:41.956
[Joe sighs uncomfortably]

50:42.044 --> 50:43.784
- Can't you ask your
husband that?

50:46.178 --> 50:47.179
- I'm asking you.

50:49.616 --> 50:50.704
[Joe laughs]

50:50.791 --> 50:54.186
- Look, I'm not keeping
a calendar

50:54.273 --> 50:55.840
of every time I see a Whitman.

50:56.928 --> 50:58.364
[Meg sighs]

50:58.451 --> 51:00.584
- Right, sorry. [laughs]

51:00.671 --> 51:01.541
- [Joe] All good.

51:02.629 --> 51:05.850
